"n.名声；知名人士 【英】 n.名人，知名人士(wi de recognition; a famous or well-publicized pe rson) 【考】 反义词：obscurity( 默默无闻) n. 知名人士; 声望 【例】social celebrities 社会名流 【根】cerebr脑 【反】obscurity(n 身份低微的人) 【记】celebrated，名人总是被祝贺称赞，整天开庆祝会 celebrity (n.)  late 14c., ""solemn rite or ceremony,"" from Old French celebrité ""celebration"" or directly from Latin celibritatem (nominative celebritas) ""multitude, fame,"" from celeber ""frequented, populous"" (see celebrate). Meaning ""condition of being famous"" is from c.1600; that of ""famous person"" is from 1849. When the old gods withdraw, the empty thrones cry out for a successor, and with good management, or even without management, almost any perishable bag of bones may be hoisted into the vacant seat. [E.R. Dodds, ""The Greeks and the Irrational""]"
